  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish common standards and principles\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating cross-border financial crimes\n- Sharing of evidence and financial intelligence\n- Extradition of suspects\n- Coordinated enforcement actions\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Consistent anti-money laundering (AML) standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Suspicious transaction reporting protocols\n- Standardized financial transparency measures\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- International monitoring of national AML frameworks\n- Peer review processes\n- Sanctions for non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Encouraging consistent implementation\n\n5. Organizational Frameworks\n- Interpol coordination\n- World Bank and IMF oversight\n- FATF blacklisting of high-risk countries\n- International collaboration on financial crime prevention\n\nThese intersections create a multilayered approach to combating money laundering globally, balancing national sovereignty with international cooperation.",
